{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606613"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:15:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:15:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15927"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15927"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.04,0.48,0.32,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8618"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114785"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8618"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96788"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8407"},{"type":"tags","id":"8701"},{"type":"tags","id":"9596"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20647"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114785"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, the appendicular skeleton forms through a process that begins with mesenchymal condensation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the sequence of long bone development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mesenchyme forms bone directly without a cartilage intermediate","Ossification begins simultaneously in all parts of the cartilage model","Cartilage model forms, followed by primary ossification in diaphysis","Cartilage model forms, followed by primary ossification in epiphyses","Primary ossification occurs simultaneously in diaphysis and epiphyses"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe process of long bone development begins with mesenchymal condensation, which differentiates into a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecartilage model\u003C/strong\u003E through chondrification. During fetal development, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary ossification centre appears in the diaphysis\u003C/strong\u003E (shaft) of the developing bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesenchyme forming bone directly\u003C/strong\u003E describes intramembranous ossification, which occurs in flat bones, not long bones. \u003Cstrong\u003EOssification beginning simultaneously in all parts\u003C/strong\u003E of the model does not follow the specific temporal sequence that characterises endochondral ossification. The statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary ossification occurs in epiphyses\u003C/strong\u003E reverses the normal sequence, as epiphyseal ossification represents secondary centres that develop after birth. \u003Cstrong\u003ESimultaneous ossification in diaphysis and epiphyses\u003C/strong\u003E contradicts the established pattern where diaphyseal ossification precedes epiphyseal development by months to years.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Long bones develop through endochondral ossification beginning with a cartilage model.","Primary ossification centres appear in the diaphysis during fetal development.","Secondary ossification centres develop in the epiphyses after birth."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96788"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions